                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18430130-765-offence-1 t18430130-name-1030"></join>John Cooper</persName>.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430130-name-1031" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430130-name-1031" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430130-name-1031" type="surname" value="COOPER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430130-name-1031" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN COOPER</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a builder, and live in Newland-street, Pimlico. On the 13th of Jan. the prisoner came and asked me to let him have my cart to sell it—I said, "No, you shall not take the cart without you bring the money first"—he had had it before for sale—he did not bring me any money for it—I did not permit him in any way to take it—he came up to me on the 21st, and said, "I am very sorry, master, I have sold your cart, and lost the money"—I said, "As soon as I can see a policeman I shall give you in charge."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430130-name-1032" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430130-name-1032" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430130-name-1032" type="surname" value="COOPER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430130-name-1032" type="given" value="FREDERICK"></interp>FREDERICK COOPER</persName>
                  </hi>. The prisoner came and asked if I would let him have the cart—I said, "Not without my father's permission"—he went away, then came back, and said my father had given him leave, and I let him have it.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184301300177"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner.</hi> His father was at the Wellington; I went there, and he gave me leave to do the best I could, and told me not to bring it home if it was late, but to take it to Mr. Digby's—the next morning I went to his build<lb></lb>ings in the Vauxhall-road, and did not see him; in coming back, I saw him, and spoke to him; he sent my brother to know whether I had told the cart; I told him when I met him that he should not lose a farthing; I would pay 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. a week; I do not live a stone's throw from him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430130-name-1033" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430130-name-1033" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430130-name-1033" type="surname" value="COOPER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430130-name-1033" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN COOPER</persName>
                  </hi>. It was above ten days before I cound find where he lived—I lost the cart on the 13th, and he did not come to me till the 21st.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Witnesses for the Defence.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430130-name-1034" type="witnessName">
